{"questionId":"20367","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Two friends Amelia and Bill, each set themselves a target of saving <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>$</mo><mn>20</mn><mo> </mo><mn>000</mn></math>. They each have&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>$</mo><mn>9000</mn></math> to invest.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A third friend Chris also wants to reach the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>$</mo><mn>20</mn><mo> </mo><mn>000</mn></math> target. He puts his money in a safe&nbsp;where he does not earn any interest. His system is to add more money to this safe&nbsp;each year. Each year he will add half the amount added in the previous year.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Show that Chris will never reach the target if his initial deposit is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>$</mo><mn>9000</mn></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>recognising geometric series (seen anywhere)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>4500</mn><mn>9000</mn></mfrac><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>EITHER</strong></p>\n<p>considering&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>S</mi><mo>∞</mo></msub></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>9000</mn><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>18000</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>correct reasoning that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>18000</mn><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>20000</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Accept <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>S</mi><mo>∞</mo></msub><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>20000</mn></math>&nbsp;only if <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>S</mi><mo>∞</mo></msub></math>&nbsp;has been calculated.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>OR</strong></p>\n<p>considering&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>S</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></math>&nbsp;for a large value of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>80</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award<em><strong> M1</strong></em> only if the candidate gives a valid reason for&nbsp;choosing a value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi></math>, where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>50</mn><mo>≤</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>80</mn></math>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>correct value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>S</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></math>&nbsp;for their <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>valid reason why Chris will not reach the target, which involves their&nbsp;choice of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi></math>, their value of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>S</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></math> and Chris’ age OR using two large&nbsp;values of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi></math> to recognize asymptotic behaviour of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>S</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></math>&nbsp;as <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>→</mo><mo>∞</mo></math>.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>R</strong><strong>1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Do not award the <em><strong>R</strong></em> mark without the preceding <em><strong>A</strong></em>&nbsp;mark.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>THEN</strong></p>\n<p>Therefore, Chris will never reach the target.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[5 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"20367","referenceCode":"21M.2.SL.TZ1.7c.i","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Show that Chris will never reach the target if his initial deposit is $9000.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"c.i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 5]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 1—Number and algebra","SL 1.4—Financial apps – compound int, annual depreciation","Topic 1—Number and algebra","SL 1.8—Sum of infinite geo sequence"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}